You can install the tool with a single command. Open your terminal and type sudo apt install exampletool. After that, you’ll see it listed when you run exampletool --help.

Once installed, the tool checks your files for common problems. These include broken links, missing punctuation, and long sentences. If it finds anything, it prints a short message to help you fix it.

Most users run the tool once a day. You can do this by adding a command to your daily workflow or shell script. This keeps your content clean and saves time during reviews.

To learn more, visit the project’s website. It offers examples, tips, and updates. You can also check the built-in help for quick guidance.
